✅ Pay-by-Bank Integration Modes — Pros & Cons
Mode	Pros	Cons
🥇 Full Redirect
(Preferred Default)	• Provides the most stable and predictable end-to-end journey with a clear linear navigation flow

• Fully aligned with bank security requirements since authentication occurs in top-level browser context

• Avoids iframe sandbox restrictions, popup blockers, and cross-window messaging complexity

• Requires the lowest engineering effort with simpler state management and navigation handling

• Easiest mode to test, automate, monitor, and debug across browsers and devices

• Strong mobile stability with no tab confusion or popup blocking behavior

• Matches common industry patterns, making the experience familiar to users	• Users temporarily leave the merchant checkout page during authentication steps

• Checkout UI and cart context are not visible while users interact with bank pages

• Experience feels less visually embedded compared to iframe-based approaches

• Flow can be interrupted if users close the tab or browser before returning

• Reduced white-label control because the Tink domain becomes visible during redirect steps
🥈 Hybrid (Embed → Redirect for Auth)	• Keeps checkout page visible during early steps like bank selection and consent, preserving shopping context

• Provides a more seamless and modern experience compared to full redirect alone

• Uses full redirect only when bank authentication begins, improving compatibility and reliability

• Balances user experience smoothness with technical robustness

• Allows merchants to present alternative payment methods alongside Pay-by-Bank in embedded view	• More complex implementation due to combining iframe embedding and full-page redirect flows

• Requires additional state synchronization between embedded content and redirect navigation

• Needs cross-window communication mechanisms with strict origin validation

• Higher QA effort due to multiple navigation patterns across browsers and devices

• iframe permissions and CSP policies must be carefully configured and maintained

• Reduced white-label control because the Tink domain becomes visible during redirect phase
🥉 Full iFrame (Popup / New Tab for Bank)	• Merchant checkout page remains visible throughout the journey, preserving full shopping context

• Delivers the most visually seamless and tightly integrated on-page user experience

• Strongest white-label presentation since users stay within merchant environment

• Useful when UI continuity and on-page embedding are high business priorities	• Desktop popup blockers may prevent bank authentication windows from opening automatically

• Mobile devices may open authentication in separate tabs, causing confusion and user drop-offs

• Many banks restrict or block authentication inside iframes due to security policies

• Users often must manually return to the original tab, creating friction in the journey

• Nested iframe layouts can introduce scrolling, sizing, and button visibility issues on small screens

• Highest engineering complexity due to popup lifecycle handling and message orchestration

• Most difficult mode to test, automate, monitor, and debug reliably
